Sideros v16  ·  The Loom weaves all. Your thread is your own.

✶  ✶  ✶

### **THE WARRING ZODIACS**

The foundational vision of Sideros

Sideros is not a world with one pantheon of gods or a single truth about the stars. It is a sphere where the divine right of the Egyptian-inspired Dragon Lords is as real as the seasonal cycle of the Celtic Oak and Holly Kings. The ancestor-spirits that guide the Mongolian-inspired Lizard-Folk are as potent as the Orishas who grant Ashé to the heroes of the Ashélands. **The laws of the cosmos are not universal; they are regional in nature.** Each culture is a living testament to its zodiac, and their truths are fundamentally incompatible.

This is what fuels the world's deepest conflicts. It is not just about politics or resources. It is about clashes of absolute, divinely-proven realities. A knight from the Leonine Empire, whose entire existence is shaped by the fading Age of the Lion, cannot comprehend the thinking of a shaman from K'uh-la'an, whose life is governed by a sacred 260-day calendar. Both are right. Both are unanswerable. Both walk the same world without sharing it.

**This foundation makes the central threat of the Ashen Coil all the more profound.** They are not just another faction trying to prove their god is superior. They are a force of cosmic heresy. They have seen this tapestry of conflicting truths and declared the entire system to be a lie — a prison of existence that must be unmade. Their goal is not conquest. Their goal is the destruction of all zodiacs, all gods, and all faiths.

The unique hook of Sideros is this: it is a world where every compass points to a different true north, and the greatest adventure lies in navigating this web of clashing destinies — all while a force that wants to shatter the compass itself grows ever stronger in the shadows.

✶  ✶  ✶

### **THE FOUR SENSES**

What Sideros should feel like at the table

**A Sense of Wonder.** To be drawn into the sheer diversity of the world. To marvel at the flying ships of Aetheria, to feel the heat of Khem-Ma'at's sun, to hear the whisper of the kami in the forests of Mori-Ōkami, and to feel that every horizon holds a new, completely different truth.

**A Sense of Agency.** To understand that the world is on a knife's edge. The Age of the Lion is ending, the Ashen Coil is rising, and the old certainties are gone. The actions of individuals — whether they are a single adventurer or the protagonist of a larger story — have the power to tip the scales and decide the fate of nations, or even the world itself.

**A Sense of Aspiration.** To see this as a world where you can truly be anything and love anyone. The freedom built into Sideros's systems is intentional. It is a place to explore complex identities, unconventional relationships, and find heroism in unexpected places — offering a powerful sense of escapism and self-discovery.

**A Sense of Hope.** Despite the grim threats and decaying empires, Sideros is not a cynical world. It is a world that is worth fighting for because of its diversity, its freedom, and its beauty. The core experience should be one of defiance against the coming darkness — a belief that even in a sundered world, connection, courage, and love can forge a better future.

✶  ✶  ✶

### **GENRE**

The kind of story Sideros tells

Sideros is not a single genre. The world spans several, allowing tone to shift from session to session — but four threads run through everything.

**Primary: Epic High Fantasy.** The world operates on a grand scale. Deep mythic history. World-spanning conflict against a cosmic evil. Powerful magic. Legendary artifacts. A diverse roster of sentient species both classical (Elves, Dwarves) and unique to Sideros. The stakes are global, and the fate of reality itself often hangs in the balance.

**Sub-genre: Mythic Fantasy.** This is the world's signature. The story is not merely influenced by mythology — it is a world where more than a dozen real-world mythological and cosmological systems (Norse, Egyptian, Mayan, Celtic, and others) are simultaneously and tangibly true. The very nature of reality, faith, and the divine becomes a source of conflict and discovery.

**Sub-genre: Dark Fantasy / Cosmic Horror.** A strong undercurrent of darkness and decay runs through Sideros. The world is in a fading age — its greatest empire crumbling, its old certainties dissolving. The Ashen Coil is not a simple dark lord seeking conquest, but a nihilistic cult that worships a void and seeks to unmake reality. Practices such as **Soul Harvesting** introduce elements of cosmic and psychological horror.

**Sub-genre: Political Intrigue.** Sideros is not a simple battlefield of good versus evil. It is a complex web of competing factions with nuanced agendas. The decline of the Leonine Empire, the rise of the fanatical Order of Pure Reason, the shadow wars conducted around the Loom of Fate, and the economic machinations of the **Grand Concord of Merchants** all create material for stories of diplomacy, espionage, and betrayal.

✶  ✶  ✶

### **TECHNOLOGY AND MAGIC**

Where the spectrum lives, and why it tilts toward magic

The balance between technology and magic in Sideros is not uniform. It exists on a broad spectrum, and in most cultures, magic is the dominant force.

**The Baseline: Iron Age / High Medieval.** For most "common" cultures — including those in the Western Realms of the Duchy Compact — baseline technology is roughly equivalent to Earth's High Middle Ages. Armies fight with steel swords, shields, and bows. Power is supplied by manual labour, animals, wind, and water. Gunpowder was not invented and is not widely known. In general, widespread magical ability has supplanted the need for major technological innovation in most societies.

Why invent a crane when a mage can lift the stone?

### **The Spectrum of Power**

| **Tier** | **Culture / Group** | **What They Have** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **High End — Magi-Tech** | The Jade Empire of Shen-lì (the most technologically advanced nation in the world) | In the Monkey Governor's domain: early industrial concepts including steam power and clockwork automation. The sentient **Gear-Forged** race emerged from this work. The Jade Empire also uses **paper currency** — a concept foreign to most other nations. |
| **Master Craftsmanship** | The Dunmarim (Dwarves) | Not technologically innovative in the Shen-lì sense, but their mastery of metallurgy, stonework, and engineering is unparalleled. Their ability to work with **Aether-Dampening Ore** is a unique technological advantage no other culture can replicate. |
| **Arcane Science** | The Comet-Magi of Argent Spire | The peak of magical understanding. They treat magic as a fundamental science. Their knowledge of the cosmos and the Aetherium is so advanced that it borders on super-science, allowing them to create effects that mimic or surpass any technology. |
| **Low-Tech / High-Magic** | The Tuathan Archipelago, the Ashélands, the Wolf-Shifters of Mori-Ōkami | Very low level of mundane technology — and no need for more. Their societies are wholly integrated with the powerful primal or divine magic of their lands. They use enchanted wood, sacred herbs, and spirit-blessed warriors instead of steel and machines. |

**What this means at the table:** Sideros is not a uniform-tech world. A character travelling from the Tuathan Archipelago to the Jade Empire experiences something close to cultural vertigo — not because the technology is unfamiliar, but because the foundational assumption about how the world is made to work changes. The Tuathan asks the land. The Shen-lì engineer asks the Geode. Both get answers. Neither is wrong.

✶  ✶  ✶

### **Introduction: What is Sideros?**

Sideros is a tabletop roleplaying game of fate, identity, and defiance. The Loom of Fate weaves every living creature's future — destiny as a literal cosmic fabric, maintained by a universe that has opinions about what should happen next. Your character is a thread in that fabric.

This matters because the primary antagonist, Aethar — the Serpent Bearer, a former 12th Circle Comet-Magus — intends to destroy the Loom entirely. Not conquer it. Not control it. End it. The consequences of fate ceasing to exist are not abstract: without the Loom, Void-Husks multiply, bonded relationships dissolve, magical paths collapse, and the world reduces to entropy. Aethar has specific reasons for wanting this. He may not be entirely wrong about the Loom's flaws. He is wrong about the solution.

### **The Loom**

The Loom is a cosmic structure that predates every civilization, every Kindred, and every recorded history. It weaves probable futures from the Aether — the fundamental energy underlying all matter and magic. Every creature has a Fate Number: a permanent numerical identifier assigned at birth that marks their position in the Loom's pattern. Numbers that fall near each other on the Loom are drawn toward Fated Bond relationships. Numbers that fall near 13, 66, or 99 carry the Hollow Serpent's resonance — Aethar's patron entity and the existential threat at the campaign's centre.

## **Paths and Depths**

Characters advance through Resonance Depths (1-20, with some Paths extending further). Each Depth represents a deepening of the character's relationship with their Path's source of power. A Depth 1 Primal Jarl has just tasted their Wrath State for the first time. A Depth 20 Primal Jarl is a force of nature comparable to the Legendary Beasts that anchor the zodiac. A Calling is chosen at Depth 3 — the specific direction within the Path that defines the character's long-term development.

### **The Ashen Coil**

The Ashen Coil is the only faction in Sideros that has stepped outside the warring zodiacs entirely. They have seen the system and rejected it. Everything else they do — the intelligence operation, the political manipulation, the Void-Husk production — is in service of that rejection.

Publicly the Coil operates as a trade syndicate, an academic society, and a network of political advisors. Privately it is a structured intelligence operation with three levels: outer-ring agents who do not know what they are part of, inner-ring operatives who know the mission but not the final stage, and the Triad (Aethar, Serath, Drava Nullsong) who know everything. The Coil produces Void-Husks, manipulates political succession crises, controls Aether-Dampening Ore supply, and actively tracks Fated Bond lineages to prevent the Quint Bond from forming.

