### **Anointed Weapons — Cultural Smith Upgrades**

Below the threshold of true magic weaponry — the +1 enchanted swords and Working-bound artefacts that take a Resonance Seeker a year to forge — there is a deep tradition of cultural anointment. A skilled smith of a specific tradition can prepare a mundane weapon to engage a specific category of foe more effectively. The weapon does not become magical. It becomes prepared.

Each anointment is performed by a smith of the named tradition. The work takes 3–7 days. Only one anointment may be active on a single weapon at a time — the frequencies of competing anointments cancel one another out. An anointment is permanent until the weapon is melted, broken beyond repair, or deliberately re-forged.

| **Anointment** | **Tradition** | **Cost** | **Effect** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **Cold-Iron Tipped** | Tuathan Hollow-Smith | 75 Marks | Bypasses resistance and damage reduction from Fae-Blooded targets, Otherworld entities, and Fade-Bleed creatures. Strike Resonances against such targets deal full damage regardless of their Aetheric defenses. |
| **Sun-Kissed Anointed** | Khem-Ma'at Solar Forge | 150 Marks | The weapon counts as Sun-Kissed Adamas for the purpose of striking Void-Husks, undead, and Hollow Serpent emanations — bypasses their resistance and adds +1d4 radiant damage to such targets. The anointment shines faintly in the presence of Void corruption (functional Void-detector at close range). |
| **Aether-Quenched** | Dunmarim Deep-Forge | 200 Marks | The weapon functions normally inside The Stillness (Aether-Dampening Ore zones), where most weapons feel inert and lifeless. Additionally: +1 to Strike Resonance rolls made within any Stillness zone. The Dunmarim are not eager to sell this upgrade to outsiders. |
| **Moon-Etched** | Tuathan Illusion-Smith (Noctilith inlay) | 100 Marks | Illusion-warded targets (Working-cloaked, Aether-Veiled, partially phased) cannot avoid the weapon by their concealment. The weapon's etched pattern is invisible in sunlight; visible silvery-white in moonlight. |
| **Bog-Etched** | Mongolian Bog-Keeper Smith | 125 Marks | On a successful Strike Resonance, the wielder may choose to suppress one ongoing condition on the target (Soul-Swayed, Dread-Struck, Corrupted, or Resonance-Shattered) for one Pulse. Once per encounter. |
| **Beast-Bound** | Beast-cultural smith (sign-specific) | 100 Marks (cultural anointment); 200 Marks (cross-cultural) | Choose one zodiac sign at the time of anointment. The weapon deals +1d6 damage to creatures of that sign's lineage (Beast-Descended, Beast-Kin morphology matching, or Emanations of that sign). Cannot be re-targeted once chosen. |
| **Lead-Suppressed** | Comet-Magi Anti-Void Inscription | 250 Marks | The weapon's edge is inscribed with anti-Lead Working glyphs. On a successful Strike against a target carrying Lead-Scale, the target makes a Resonance Warding Resonance (Threshold 14) or loses one Lead-Scale level. The weapon also registers in Kallos-Sworn records — Comet-Magi will recognize and may question the wielder. |
| **Star-Inked** | Stellar Cartographer Tradition (Sagittarian Steppes) | 175 Marks | The weapon is inscribed with the wielder's Fate Number in faint star-script along the blade. Once per Deep Attunement, the wielder may declare a Reading on a target before striking — Acuity Active Resonance (Threshold 14) to read the target's Fate Number. On success, +1d6 damage on the next Strike Resonance against that target before next Brief Attunement. |

**Stacking rule:** A weapon may carry **one** anointment at a time. Re-anointment requires fully removing the previous one (a 1-day ritual at any of the originating smiths, 50 Marks) before the new one can be applied.

**Cultural identification:** A practiced smith of any tradition can identify another tradition's anointment on sight (Acuity Active Resonance, Threshold 10). The mark of a Khem-Ma'at solar smith is gold-flecked; the mark of a Dunmarim deep-forge smith is a black-iron inlay. Anointed weapons are read as cultural objects, not just tools, and may carry diplomatic weight when displayed.

**Note on +1 enchanted weapons:** Anointed weapons are NOT enchanted weapons. They do not bypass damage resistance to "non-magical attacks" — they only bypass the specific resistance their anointment is designed for. A Cold-Iron Tipped longsword still cannot harm a creature resistant to non-magical weapons unless that creature also has the Fae-Blooded/Otherworld vulnerability the anointment addresses.

### **Cultural Weapons**

The weapons listed above are the common forms — what you find for sale in most market stalls across the Duchy Compact and similar trade-aware regions. Beyond them, each culture maintains its own martial traditions, with weapons that may look strange to outside eyes but are perfectly normal in the hands of those raised with them. A character with martial weapon Mastery is considered Mastered in all cultural variants of their existing Mastery category — a Solar Guard knows what to do with a Katana even if they've never held one. Some cultural weapons have unique properties; these are noted in the rightmost column.

