### **Aetheric Artifact Rarity**

Magical items in Sideros are called Aetheric Artifacts. They are categorized by rarity, attunement requirement, and cultural provenance. The rarity tiers below are guidelines for both purchase price (when available — which is rare for higher tiers) and discovery frequency.

| **Rarity** | **Approximate Value** | **Typical Source** | **Sideros Examples** | **Attunement** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **Common** | 50–100 gm | Single-use scrolls, minor charms, low-tier Anointed weapons, Working-tuned compasses | Working Scroll (1-use), Resonance-Tuned Compass, Khem-Ma'at Solar Disk Pendant, Mori-Ōkami Clan Tassel, Babalawo Beaded Ifá Cord | Usually none |
| **Uncommon** | 100–500 gm | Anointed weapons (higher tiers), simple Aetheric Artifacts, +1 weapons or armor | Cold-Iron Tipped Tuathan blade, Khem-Ma'at Sun-Kissed Anointed weapon, Asha-Crystal Pendant (Chinvat), Resonant Geode Pendant (Shen-lì), low-tier Resonant Frame components | May require attunement |
| **Rare** | 500–5,000 gm | +2 weapons/armor, Mantles of [Beast], permanent Aetheric Infusions, lesser Apex Fragments (T1–T2 reagents) | Star-Inked Steppe Sabre, Lead-Suppressed Comet-Magus blade, lesser Mantle of one of the Twelve Beasts, Accord-Maker permanent Infusion, T1 Apex Fragment (Peripheral Trace) | Almost always requires attunement |
| **Very Rare** | 5,000–50,000 gm | +3 weapons/armor, full Beast-Mantle artifacts, T3 Apex Fragments, Comet-Magus working-grade implements | Black-Iron Aether-Quenched +3 weapon, full Beast-Mantle (Sky-Witness Cloak, Crystal-Stinger Vest, etc.), Comet-Magus Resonant Implement, T3 Apex Fragment (Resonant Core), Stellar Cartographer's Annotated Lens | Requires attunement |
| **Legendary** | 50,000+ gm (often not for sale) | T4 Apex Harvests, Solar Throne regalia, Crown-grade items, Grand Prime Forgeman's work | Star-Metal Antler Tine (a confirmed Resonant Binding component), Great Roc Shed Feather (a confirmed Resonant Binding component), Solar Throne Regalia (Khem-Ma'at), Crown of the Twelfth-Plus-One (Shen-lì state), Grand Prime Forgeman's Frame, Comet-Magus 12th Circle implement | Requires attunement; often restricted to specific Path or lineage |
| **Aetheric Artifact (Apex-grade)** | Priceless | The Loom's own threads, Crystalline Core fragments, the Resonant Binding once assembled | The Loom of Fate threads, fragments of the Crystalline Core beneath Argent Spire, the fully-assembled Resonant Binding components, the Hollow Serpent's signal-crystal | Cannot be attuned; the artifact attunes to the holder, often without consent |

**Attunement rules:** A character may attune to up to **three Aetheric Artifacts** simultaneously. Attunement requires a Brief Attunement of focused interaction with the artifact (typically reading runes, wielding in practice, sleeping with it nearby — the artifact tells you what it needs). Attuning to a fourth requires breaking attunement with one of the existing three. Some artifacts are restricted to specific Paths, Kindreds, or sign-Attunements; the artifact's cultural origin determines its restrictions.

**Cultural provenance:** Aetheric Artifacts carry the marks of their making. A Resonance Seeker-crafted +1 weapon reads differently to an Acuity Active Resonance than an Accord-Maker-Infused +1 weapon (which is technically not magical — it is contractually enhanced). Most cultures can identify the provenance of an Artifact on sight (Acuity Active Resonance, Threshold 12).

### **Mounts and Vehicles**

The Sagittarian Steppes is the world's horse market. The Boreal Expanse runs on draft mules and reindeer-equivalent stock. The Moana-kin do not ride; they sail. A character's transport is rarely incidental — what you ride says something about where you came from.

| **Mount** | **Speed** | **Vitality** | **Cost** | **Notes** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **Pony** | 40 ft | 11 | 30 gm | Small mount. Most Kuri who ride choose pony. Smaller load capacity. |
| **Riding Horse** | 60 ft | 13 | 75 gm | Standard mount. Common across the Duchies. |
| **Draft Horse** | 40 ft | 19 | 50 gm | Heavy hauling. Pulls carts and wagons. Slow but enduring. |
| **Mule** | 40 ft | 11 | 8 gm | Cheap, sure-footed, surprisingly patient. Standard for caravan and mountain travel. |
| **Warhorse** | 60 ft | 19 | 400 gm | Trained for combat. Adds +2 to its rider's Strike Resonance damage on a charge (10+ ft straight movement). Reflex Strikes against riders of warhorses have Resonant Discord. |
| **Camel** | 50 ft | 15 | 50 gm | Desert mount. Goes 3 days without water. Refuses cold weather (Aurelian campaigns only). |
| **Steppe Horse (Sagittarian)** | 60 ft | 15 | 150 gm | Bred on the Steppes — endurance superior to standard. May Dash twice per encounter without exhaustion. Available only through Steppe Rider Origin contacts or extensive trade. |
| **Frost Reindeer (Boreal)** | 40 ft | 17 | 80 gm | Pulls sleds and bears riders in deep snow. Treats arctic terrain as normal. |
| **Centaur-Kin** | N/A | (character) | N/A | Centaur-Kin do not have mounts. They are mounts when carrying others — and they choose whom. |

### **Vehicles**

| **Vehicle** | **Speed** | **Capacity** | **Cost** | **Notes** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **Handcart** | Walk pace | 200 lb | 5 gm | One person can pull. |
| **Cart** | Mount speed | 500 lb | 15 gm | Single-horse drawn. Standard farm and small merchant transport. |
| **Wagon** | 30 ft (mount) | 1 ton | 35 gm | Two-horse. Roofed versions add 10 gm. Standard caravan vehicle. |
| **Carriage** | 30 ft (mount) | 4 passengers | 100 gm | Four-wheel, enclosed. Status item — nobility, wealthy merchants. |
| **Rowboat** | 1.5 mph | 4 passengers | 50 gm | Inland waters and coastal short hops. |
| **Sailing Ship** | 2 mph cruising | 100 tons / 80 passengers | 10,000 gm | Standard merchant vessel. Crew of 20. Requires Navigator's Tools to handle in open water. |
| **Galley** | 4 mph (oars+sail) | 150 tons / 80 crew | 30,000 gm | Military vessel. Most Duchy Compact navies operate galleys. |
| **Waka (Moana-kin Longboat)** | 3 mph cruising, 6 mph in wind | 6 passengers | 200 gm | Single-hulled with outrigger. Cannot capsize when operated by a Moana-kin Navigator. Standard Ara Moana craft. |
| **Waka Hourua (Twin-Hulled)** | 4 mph cruising | 20 passengers + 5 tons | 2,500 gm | Twin-hulled ocean voyaging canoe. Used for the long Te Moana-nui passages. |
| **Skiff (Te Kapo)** | 2 mph in still water | 2 passengers | 40 gm | Flat-bottomed for cave waters. Te Kapo Wayfinding equivalent of a rowboat. |

### **Trinkets**

Every Sideros character begins with one Trinket, if they choose. Roll d100 or select. These are world-anchoring objects — small, often inexplicable, and frequently more interesting in play than they appeared at character creation.

| **d100** | **Trinket** |
| --- | --- |
| 1 | A Precursor coin that no scholar can date. The script on it is not in any known catalogue. |
| 2 | A vial of clear water sealed with wax. The seal bears a wave-pattern of the Pre-Fall era. |
| 3 | A small brass key with no record of its lock. Cold to the touch. |
| 4 | A child's drawing of a person you do not recognize. The signature is your own. |
| 5 | A glass eye that occasionally feels warm. |
| 6 | A pressed flower from a species not native to your homeland. |
| 7 | A scrap of paper with a name written in your handwriting. You have never met this person. |
| 8 | An iron ring that turns warm in the presence of a lie. (Not reliable — turns warm sometimes for other reasons too.) |
| 9 | A coil of black thread that never tangles, no matter how it is stored. |
| 10 | A folded map showing a city that does not exist. |
| 11 | A Comet-Magi student's notebook with three pages torn out. |
| 12 | A wooden carving of a small animal. The carving's species changes when no one watches it directly. |
| 13 | A silver locket with a strand of hair the same colour as yours. |
| 14 | A small mirror that briefly reflects rooms you have never been in, but only when you are not looking. |
| 15 | A piece of obsidian glass shaped like a falling leaf. |
| 16 | A bone die that always rolls 13 if you don't look at it as you throw. |
| 17 | A jar of honey with a bee preserved inside, perfectly intact. Bees are calm in your presence. |
| 18 | A scroll case sealed with Kallos-Sworn wax. The scroll inside is blank. |
| 19 | A small wooden bird that will sing one phrase if you ask the right question. You don't know what the right question is. |
| 20 | A piece of dark wood that smells faintly of the ocean even when held inland. |
| 21 | A worn leather glove for the left hand. It fits perfectly. |
| 22 | A heavy iron pendant in the shape of a Roman Roman numeral XIII. Cold even in summer. |
| 23 | A pearl that hums when held over deep water. |
| 24 | A folded cloth that, when unfolded, is always the same size — never larger, never smaller. |
