### **Cultural Currency Customs**

Marks are the closest thing to a universal currency, but cultures differ sharply in what they accept, what they prefer, and what is rude to offer. Travelers who fail to adapt to local custom find their Marks accepted but their welcome curdled.

| **Culture** | **Primary Medium** | **Notes on Use** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Duchy Compact / Aurelian** | Marks (standard) | Aurelian Treasury mints all Duchy Compact Marks. Universally accepted across affiliated territories. |
| **Khem-Ma****'****at** | Marks + Solar Treasury notes | The Solar Throne mints its own gold equivalent (interchangeable with gm at parity). Major contracts go through the Solar Bourse. Tax-free transactions are unusual and noticed. |
| **Mori-Ōkami** | Marks accepted; clan-honor primary | Clan ledgers track honour-debts. Outsiders pay in Marks but lose social standing if they refuse the honour-exchange entirely. |
| **K****'****uh-la****'****an** | **Weep-Stone primary**; Marks accepted secondarily | Weep-Stone charges (400 gm each) are the prestige currency. Major contracts are denominated in Weep-Stone, even when paid in Marks. |
| **Moana-kin (Te Moana-nui)** | **Barter / reputation** | Marks are alien to deep-archipelago Moana-kin culture. Trade is in goods, oaths, navigational debts. Marks accepted only at port towns; offering them at a longhouse is mildly rude. |
| **Tuathan** | Marks / oaths / specific items | Marks accepted in mortal-world trade. Hedge-folk and Otherworld-adjacent figures accept oaths or specific items (an iron nail, a thing that was loved). **Noctilith has no monetary value within Tuathan culture.** |
| **Dunmar** | Marks above-ground; barter below | Marks accepted in surface markets. Below-ground trade is barter — Black Iron specifically is **rejected as currency**. Dunmar Vault-Keepers offer the most secure deep-storage banking in the world. |
| **Boreal Expanse** | Marks + guest-gift / oath | Reputation-economy. Cash transactions are rude in Jarl-halls. Guest-gifts expected to roughly match the value of the Marks-equivalent received in hospitality. |
| **Shen-lì (Jade Empire)** | Imperial Marks + Resonant Geode dust | Imperial Treasury mints its own equivalent (parity with Duchy Marks). Resonant Geode dust is the **industrial currency** for Gear-Forged construction and Frame repair. |
| **Chinvat** | Marks + truth-oaths | Cash accepted at all levels. High-value contracts (5,000+ gm) require an **Asha-witnessed oath** in addition to payment. Default contract law presumes the oath alongside the Marks. |
| **Ashélands** | Marks + Iyanifa-blessed cowries | Cowries (sm equivalent) circulate in Iyanifa-sanctioned trade — markets blessed by a Babalawo. Marks for everything else. Counterfeit cowries are a serious crime. |
| **Sagittarian Steppes** | Marks + horse-wealth | Horses are the primary store of wealth. Marks acceptable for portable goods only. Star-Reading clans use **star-marked tokens** for inter-clan settlement. |
| **Te Kapo (caves)** | **Barter only** | Marks largely useless. Trade in surface goods for cave-resources (mushrooms, bioluminescence, Void-glass). Offering Marks is not insulting — it's confusing. |

### **Banking and Letters of Credit**

Carrying 5,000 gm in coin means carrying 100 lbs of metal. For high-value transactions over distance, banking institutions issue letters of credit — paper or sealed-token instruments redeemable at affiliated offices in distant cities. Most major institutions charge a 1–3% fee for issuance.

| **Institution** | **Cultural Origin** | **Services Offered** | **Fee** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **Silk Road Guild** | Trans-cultural (most major ports) | Letters of credit; redeemable at any Guild office; presence in every major trade hub. Most universal banking option. | 2% |
| **Dunmar Vault-Keepers** | Dunmarim Stone Kingdom | High-security physical storage (vault rentals 10 gm/year for small box; large vaults negotiable). Cannot transfer between Dunmar holds — Dunmar trusts stone, not paper. | 5 gm/year minimum |
| **Khem-Ma****'****at Solar Treasury** | Khem-Ma'at | State banking. Letters of Solar Credit accepted in any city recognizing the Solar Throne. Politically loaded — Solar Throne records every transaction. | 1% |
| **Aurelian Merchants****'**** Bourse** | Duchy Compact | Coin exchange at standard rates; traveler's credit notes for cross-Duchy travel. Reliable but unimaginative; cannot transfer outside Duchy territory. | 2% |
| **Aetheria Resonant Archive** | Comet-Magi institutional | Does not handle Marks. Acts as intermediary for high-value Aetheric assets, Working obligations, and Conclave-witnessed agreements. Not banking in the conventional sense. | Service-based |
| **Coil ****"****Charitable Trust****"** | Ashen Coil (clandestine) | Letters of credit at suspiciously favourable rates (0.5% fee). Each use creates an obligation file. Avoid. | 0.5% — but you become the product |

### **Letter of Credit mechanics:**

- **Issue cost:** 1–3% of face value, one-time

- **Redemption:** Anywhere within issuing institution's network

- **Expiry:** 1 year typical; some institutions issue indefinite

- **Security:** Issuing institution verifies identity at both ends. Counterfeit letters carry severe penalties (Duchy Compact: 5-year hard labour; Khem-Ma'at: branded and exiled; Dunmar: forfeit-of-clan).

### **Black Market and Coil Trade**

Parallel economies exist for materials that are criminal to possess in most jurisdictions. The Coil controls supply for several. Possession is criminal; trade is risky; but the materials change hands.

| **Material / Service** | **Black Market Price** | **Legal Risk** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Lead-Trace dagger** | 200 gm (vs. 5 sm for a legal copper dagger of similar form) | Possession criminal in every recognised civilization. On hit: +1 Lead-Scale to target. Kallos-Sworn track Lead-Trace circulation. |
| **Void-Touched Crystal (raw)** | 800 gm/oz | Arrest in every civilization recognising the substance. Coil controls supply. Possession = political execution in Khem-Ma'at; long imprisonment in Duchy Compact. |
| **Smuggled Aether-Dampening Ore** | 7,000+ gm/unit (vs. 5,000 gm legal grey market) | Dunmarim double-agents handle extraction. Severe Dunmar penalties if traced; party becomes Dunmar-blacklisted. |
| **Falsified Comet-Magi credentials** | 500 gm | Forgery; immediate Comet-Magi response if discovered. Conclave never forgets. |
| **Coil ****"****philanthropy****"**** gift** (minor) | 50 gm donation → minor introduction or favour | Each "favour" tracked. Eventual call-in is not optional. |
| **Coil ****"****philanthropy****"**** gift** (major) | 500 gm donation → mid-tier favour | The favour you receive is real. The cost is also real. |
| **Cultural artifact (looted)** | 200–5,000 gm (depending on artifact) | Returning the artifact to its origin culture is sometimes the only legal resolution. Khem-Ma'at and Mori-Ōkami pursue looted items across generations. |
| **Forgery of identity documents** | 100–500 gm | Common in Port Damaris; reliable forgers exist; legal consequences vary by jurisdiction. |
| **Working scroll (illegal Working)** | 200% of legal Working scroll price | Some Workings are banned in specific jurisdictions (Charm Person banned in Khem-Ma'at; Speak with Dead restricted in Tuathan territory). |

### **Aetheric Obligation as Soft Currency**

Comet-Magi do not transact in Marks for their services. They record obligations. A Comet-Magus who casts a Working for you does not invoice — they note the obligation in the Resonant Archive, where it can be called in later. The same is true of Kallos-Sworn (who track Aetheric-aware debts), Kanya-Siddha (who track lives saved), and the Stellar Cartographer secret tradition (who track Fate-Number readings issued).

An Aetheric Obligation outweighs any Marks value in the institutions that recognise it. A character who has helped a Comet-Magi Initiate during their qualifying ritual carries an Obligation that no amount of money can replicate — and that the Conclave will honour years later, often at unexpected moments.

Obligations are not the same as the Fang of the Whisper's "favour" system (which carries threat). Aetheric Obligation is institutionally recorded, transparent, and binding on both parties. The Coil cannot replicate it — which is one reason the Coil is suspicious of all things Comet-Magi.

